  <article itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/UserComments" id="comment-2089101" class="single-comment">
    <div>
      <header>        <div>
                      <a href="/users/specialed41/comments" title="View specialed41&#039;s profile">specialed41</a>                                <time itemprop="dateCreated" dateTime="2013-07-16T02:00:00+0000" class="created" title="2013-07-16T02:00:34+00:00">Jul 16th 2013 2:00 GMT</time>
        </div>
      </header>
      <div class="comment-body"><p>It seems to me that the article leaves out some important areas, which makes it impossible to form an opinion about what should be done.  First, is ther anything in the UN charter or other governing documents that grants the organization any form of immunity from liability for actions to aid a member state or taken in pursuit of a General Assembly or Council directive?  While we might all agree that the General Secretary's handling of the issue into put it in the kindest terms, ham handed, it could be that he is simply defending the organization's charter.  To illustrate, is the UN liable if one of its peacekeeping forces kills innocent civilians accidentally or deliberately?  If the UN is not liable by virtue of being protected by a status akin to that accorded most national governments, does this immunity extend to nation states acting under the aegis of a UN mandate?  I can think of a dozen more similar questions, all of which need answers in order for the reader to comprehend this issue.  In the end, by simply railing against the UN, the Economist failed to meet its own jounalistic standards in preparing this article.</p>
</div>
      <footer class="clearfix">
                  <ul class="links"><li class="comment_recommend first"><a href="/vote/recommend-comment/2089101?nid=21581878&amp;page=0&amp;sort=0&amp;token=3bwn jounalistic standards in preparing this article.</p>
</div>
