  <article class="permalink last"><a href="http://www.economist.com/comment/20889itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/UserComments" id="comment-2088358" class="single-comment">
    <div>
      <header>        <div>
                      <a href="/users/sfYiD63Qgv/comments" title="View sfYiD63Qgv&#039;s profile">sfYiD63Qgv</a>                                <time itemprop="dateCreated" dateTime="2013-07-15T19:02:00+0000" class="created" title="2013-07-15T19:02:12+00:00">Jul 15th 2013 19:02 GMT</time>
        </div>
      </header>
      <div class="comment-body"><p>By honestly accepting responsibility the UN could have strengthened, or at least maintained, its respectability.<br />
But these weasel words about "immunity" make me weep for the organization where I worked for many years as a field representative.<br />
The UN as an institution often gets blamed for actions or, more often, inactions which are in fact the consequences of decisions by its member states.<br />
In this case it is the Secretariat itself.<br />
Mr. Ban would surely count on political support from member states if he decided to over-rule the desk-warmers in Legal Office.  If he feels this is impossible, he should take a principled stand and resign in protest. Otherwise, we can only assume he agrees that the UN"s "privileges" are more important than the lives of Haitians.</p>
</div>
