  <article itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/UserComments" id="comment-2088074" class="single-comment">
    <div>
      <header>        <div>
                      <a href="/users/femi/comments" title="View femi&#039;s profile">femi</a>                                <time itemprop="dateCreated" dateTime="2013-07-15T13:24:00+0000" class="created" title="2013-07-15T13:24:31+00:00">Jul 15th 2013 13:24 GMT</time>
        </div>
      </header>
      <div class="comment-body"><p>From a public international law point of view this is going to be a very interesting case and indeed a locus classicus. However as this article rightly points out this case is going to have serious implications for NGO and other quasi-governmental organisations who volunteer to take on aid work. Again we seem to be lurching away from common sense and seeking once again legal remedies to problems which should really be resolved by other means.In the end volunteers and those who could otherwise bring aid, succor or relief in times of crisis are going to be reluctant to do so in future, with the consequence that we would see people suffer and die where help could otherwise be provided. How utterly devoid of common sense , but this is a reflection of the world we are now creating. It is unfortunate that it would have to come to this.</p>
</div>
