  <article itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/UserComments" id="comment-2090838" class="single-comment">
    <div>
      <header>        <div>
                      <a href="/users/Hussain%2BAlrikabi/comments" title="View Hussain Alrikabi&#039;s profile">Hussain Alrikabi</a>                                <time itemprop="dateCreated" dateTime="2013-07-17T13:48:00+0000" class="created" title="2013-07-17T13:48:27+00:00">Jul 17th 2013 13:48 GMT</time>
        </div>
      </header>
      <div class="comment-body"><p>The members of US Congress who had urged the UN to take responsibility of the cholera outbreak in Haiti are to be commended for their concern. However, not a single member of the US Congress has ever urged his own government to take responsibility for the horrible effects on the health of Iraqis, particularly children, from the depleted uranium bombs which were generously showered on Iraq by the US during the Gulf War of 1991. In fact the US still denies the fact that depleted uranium bombs were used by US armed forces in Iraq. The United States of America is quite selective about moral responsibilities. That's why it is better for US Administrations and Congress members not to assume high moral ground and to refrain from commenting on such matters until they first own to the US instigated horrors afflicting the human race.<br />
Hussain Alrikabi<br />
3 Cronia Court, Wheelers Hill, Victoria 3150, Australia, <a href="mailto:h.alrikabi@gmail.com" rel="nofollow">h.alrikabi@gmail.com</a></p>
